[3] Australia: (NT Government)
Date: Wed 27 Mar 2019
Source: Katherine Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.katherinetimes.com.au/story/5978150/measles-outbreak-prompts-nt-government-to-lower-baby-vaccine-age/?cs=1459


Northern Territory Government has lowered the age when babies can be vaccinated in urgent response to a measles outbreak in Darwin.

Babies can now receive the free measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine at 9 months of age instead of 12 months.

Reported cases of the highly infectious disease in the Darwin area continue to rise, while no confirmed cases have been reported in Katherine. There are now 23 confirmed cases of people with measles.

"The NT Government is providing Territorians with access to quality health care, and we have responded to the recent measles outbreak by offering the free MMR vaccine earlier to babies," Minister for Health, Natasha Fyles said.

[Byline: Roxanne Fitzgerald]

