[6] Hong Kong: vaccine policy
Date: Wed 27 Mar 2019 5:30 PM HKT
Source: South China Morning Post [abridged, edited]
https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/health-environment/article/3003500/hong-kong-change-measles-vaccine-policy-so


Hong Kong is set to change its vaccination policy for measles, with children receiving a 2nd injection against the contagious disease at a younger age amid a continuous rise in infections.

From next year [2020], children aged 18 months will receive the 2nd jab instead of having to wait until they are 6 years old under the existing policy.

Secretary for Food and Health Professor Sophia Chan Siu-chee also revealed at the Legislative Council on Wed that about 30 000 doses of the vaccine would arrive in Hong Kong next month [April 2019]. The Airport Authority would also step up its vaccination service for airport staff.

Chan's announcement came as the Department of Health confirmed 4 more cases of measles, taking this year's [2019] total to 30.

The 4 cases included 2 from the airport -- a 31-year-old man working at the MTR's Airport Station, and a 21-year-old woman working in Terminal 1. By [Wed 27 Mar 2019], a total of 11 cases involved airport and airline personnel.

The 2 other cases recorded on [Wed 27 Mar 2019] were a 43-year-old man who recently visited Okinawa, and an 8-month-old boy who recently travelled to Bangkok and Hua Hin in Thailand. He was the 3rd and youngest baby to be infected with measles this year [2019].

More measles cases likely to hit Hong Kong, disease expert warns

The city has already clocked up 20 infections so far this year [2019], more than in all of 2018.
The Centre for Health Protection steps up efforts to vaccinate workers at the airport, where the outbreak appears to have hit.

[Byline: Tony Cheung, Alvin Lum]

