[13] USA (California, Shasta, Tehama, and Butte counties)
Date: Sun 24 Mar 2019 11:32 AM EDT
Source: Record Searchlight [abridged, edited]
https://www.redding.com/story/news/2019/03/24/measles-cluster-found-shasta-tehama-and-butte-counties/3264297002/


A measles case reported in Shasta county is also related to 2 others reported in Butte and Tehama counties, health officials said [Sun 24 Mar 2019].

The female patient in Shasta county apparently caught the disease from her father, who recently had been traveling overseas when he contracted the illness, said Dr Karen Ramstrom, Shasta county's health officer.

"The (measles) cases in the United States now are often most typically connected to international travel," Ramstrom said.

She did not know the patient's immunization history, except to say "she was not adequately immunized."

Health officials are trying to contain the measles cases by isolating the patients and by reaching anyone who may have come in contact with either of the 3 people known to have the illness. Family members of those with measles have also been isolated, she said.

Ramstrom said the one patient is isolated at a Shasta county health facility, but she doesn't live in the county. She did not want to specifically identify where the other 2 patients were from except to say the 3 cases were spread across the 3 counties.

Terri Fields Hosler, Shasta county's director of public health, said she had to be careful about the patients' privacy by giving out too much personal information about the 3 people and their relationship.

She did, however, say the 3 cases constituted a "cluster," which means they have all come in direct contact with each other.

Since the 1st case was reported in Shasta county last week, no new cases have been identified, she said.

[Byline: Damon Arthur]

