[16] Ukraine: 32 939 cases
Date: Tue 26 Mar 2019
Source: Famagusta Gazette [abridged, edited]
http://famagusta-gazette.com/2019/03/26/measles-outbreak-claims-14-lives-in-ukraines/


Totally, an estimated 35 people have died of measles in Ukraine since the start of the outbreak of the disease in 2017.

At least 14 people died and more than 32 000 were infected in a major measles outbreak in Ukraine in the past 3 months.

A total of 32 939 people, including 18 109 children, were infected from 28 Dec 2018-12 Mar 2019 by measles in Ukraine, the ministry said in a statement.

Last year [2018], 35 120 cases of measles were recorded in Ukraine nationwide compared with 4782 cases confirmed in 2017. It marked the largest increase in measles cases in the world, according to the United Nations International Children's Emergency Fund (UNICEF).

The Ukrainian health authorities blamed the low level of immunization for the outbreak of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The outbreak of measles in the Ukraine with more than 32 000 people infected appears to be out of control. Early in 2018, WHO posted "WHO and partners have been working closely with the affected countries' health authorities to protect their populations from measles, as well as from other serious vaccine-preventable diseases. "At least twice as many children were vaccinated on time against measles in 2017 compared to in 2016," says the WHO Representative in Ukraine, Dr Marthe Everard. "This jump in routine immunization coverage represents a great step forward. However, the continuing spread of measles in Ukraine demonstrates that more must be done to vaccinate all those who have fallen behind." Ukraine has had the lowest immunization coverage in the Region in recent years and therefore has a large population of susceptible individuals.

Substantial progress in the past year in Ukraine includes: establishment of a national measles task force and a response plan to urgently address the outbreak; catch-up campaigns for children up to 10 years old; development of a long-term plan to ensure secure supplies of vaccines; training for health workers in identifying and reporting measles cases. (WHO Regional Office for Europe http://www.euro.who.int/en/countries/ukraine/news/news/2018/01/ukraines-efforts-to-stop-measles-outbreak-continue-as-case-total-increases)

Yet there are almost as many cases this year, 2019, in the 1st 3 months of the year, as in all 2018. Was the vaccination effort not sustained? - Mod.LK

